Actually working with dplyr

we will be playing around with the many types of subseting: filter is the main one, select allows you to pull out specific columns +mutate allows you to add a new column. Summarize columns is if you made a summary stat such as mean that gives you a single value. Finally arrange() allows you to rearrange rows Group by: lets you work with groups

for all verbs: 1. the first argument is a df 2. describe what you are going to do with your data 3. result is a new df

filter - pulling rows out

filter(gapminder, lifeExp < 29) # returns only those rows that meet this criteria

group_by()so that we can get 2 maxes

gapminder%>%
  filter(country %in% c("Egypt", "Vietnam")) %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarize(max_gdpPercap= max(gdpPercap))
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   country max_gdpPercap
##     <chr>         <dbl>
